\multirow{5}{*}{Player 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{L} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{M} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{H} \\ \cline{3-5} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{L} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{6,6}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{2,8}
                           & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,4}\\ \cline{3-5} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{M}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{8,2}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{4,4}   & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,2}\\ \cline{3-5} 
                           & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{H} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{4,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{3,-1}
                           & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,2}\\ \cline{3-5}
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
Notice that the best response is not always unique. For example, when Player 2 plays H, then both M and H are the best for Player 1, and therefore, $BR_1(H)=\{M, H\}$.
\par
Find the best responses for the rest of the pure strategies.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example 4: Cournot Duopoly}
    Consider Cournot Duopoly example with demand $p(q)=100-q$, if $q<100$, and $p(q)=0$ if $q\geq 100$, and $q=q_1+q_2$. The costs of both firms are $c_1(q_1)=10q_1$, $c_2(q_2)=10q_2$. 
     The strategic form of the game is:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item \textbf{Players:} $N=\{1,2\}$.
        \item \textbf{Actions:} $A_1=A_2=[0,\infty)$.
        \item \textbf{Payoffs:} $$u_1(q_1,q_2)=\begin{cases}(100-q_1-q_2)q_1-10q_1, & \text{ if } q_1+q_2<100,  \\
        -10q_1, & \text{ if } q_1+q_2 \geq 100. 
        \end{cases}$$
        $$ u_2(q_1,q_2)=\begin{cases}(100-q_1-q_2)q_2-10q_2, & \text{ if } q_1+q_2<100,  \\
        -10q_2, & \text{ if } q_1+q_2 \geq 100. 
        \end{cases} $$
    \end{enumerate}

\end{frame}








\begin{frame}{Example 4: Cournot Duopoly}


Notice that if $q_2\geq 100$, the best response of firm 1 will be not to produce at all. In that case, $BR(q_2)=0$. 
\par
Consider the first profit function of firm 1:
\[u_1(q_1,q_2)=(100-q_1-q_2)q_1-10q_1= 90 q_1-q_1^2-q_1q_2.
\]
If firm 2 chooses to produce $q_2$ amount, then firm 1 would choose $q_1$ that maximizes profits. Firm 1 solves, 
\[\max_{q_1}90 q_1-q_1^2-q_1q_2
\]
FOC: $90-2q_1-q_2=0$. 
SOC: $-2<0$. Second order condition is satisfied. 

Therefore the best response is solving first order condition. 
\[q_1=\frac{90-q_2}{2}.
\]
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Example 4: Cournot Duopoly}
Suppose that firm 2 produces $q_2=10$ units. Then the best response of firm 1 will be 
\[q_1=\frac{90-q_2}{2}=\frac{90-10}{2}=\frac{80}{2}=40.
\]
So, $BR_1(q_2=10)=40$.
Another example, Suppose firm 2 produces $q_2=60$ units. Then the best response of firm 1 will be 
\[q_1=\frac{90-q_2}{2}=\frac{90-60}{2}=\frac{30}{2}=15.
\]
So, $BR_1(q_2=60)=15$.
\par
As you can see, if firm 2 produces less, then firm 1 can produce more. However, when firm 2 produces more, firm 1 has to produce less. 
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Example 4: Cournot Duopoly}
What happens if firm 2 produces more than 90 units? Suppose that firm 2 produces $q_2=92$ units. Then the best response of firm 1 will be 
\[q_1=\frac{90-q_2}{2}=\frac{90-92}{2}=\frac{-2}{2}=-1<0.
\]
In this case, if $q_2\geq 90$, then firm 1 will be better off not producing anything. 
\par 
We can summarize the best response correspondence of firm 1 below:
\[ BR_1(q_2)=\begin{cases}
\frac{90-q_2}{2}, & \text{ if } 0\leq q_2\leq 90,\\
0, & \text{ if }  q_2\geq 90.
\end{cases}
\]


\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Split or Steal?}
    \begin{itemize}
      
        \item Each student has two actions to choose from: Steal or Split. 
        \item If both students choose to split, then they both will get 1 extra credit. If one student chooses to split and the other chooses to steal, than the student who played Steal will get $2$ extra credit and the student who played Split will get 0. In case both students choose to steal, they both will end up with 0 extra credit. 
        \item To participate in this activity, you must fill the google form: name of your opponent, your name and NetID, and your strategy. 
  
    \end{itemize}
          \bigskip
      \Large  \href{https://forms.gle/WNttuhLHvmAfDcq48}{https://forms.gle/WNttuhLHvmAfDcq48}
    \end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Split or Steal?}
  \begin{table}[]
\centering

%\label{my-label}
\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Student 2}                                    \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Student 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Split} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Steal} \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Split} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,1}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0, 2}   \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Steal}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{2,0}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\begin{itemize}
    \item  $BR_1(Split)= \pause Steal$, $BR_2(Split)= \pause Steal$. Notice that the best response of Split is always to Steal.
    \item $BR_1(Steal)=\pause \{Split, Steal\}$ and $BR_2(Steal)=\{Split, Steal\}$. If Student 2 plays Steal, Student 1 is indifferent between Steal and Split, and therefore both strategies are best response. 
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Mixed Strategy}
Suppose two partners are having an argument. At some point during their fight, each of them realizes that they have two options: argue or listen to their partner. The payoffs are in the matrix below. 
    
    \begin{table}[]
\centering

%\label{my-label}
\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Partner 2}                                    \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Partner 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Argue} \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-1, 1}   \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Argue}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,-1}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-2,-2}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
\end{tabular}
\end{table}


Partner 1 is thinking:
\par 
\textit{If my partner listens to me, I would argue my point. However, from the past, I know that $25\%$ of the time my partner listens to me, and $75\%$ of the time my partner argues. What is the best for me, to argue or to listen?}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Mixed Strategy}
    \begin{table}[]
\centering

%\label{my-label}
\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Partner 2}                                    \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Partner 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Argue} \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-1, 1}   \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Argue}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,-1}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-2,-2}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Partner 1 is thinking:
\par 
 \textit{"If my partner listens to me, I would argue my point. However, from the past, I know that $25\%$ of the time my partner listens to me, and $75\%$ of the time my partner argues. What is the best for me, to argue or to listen?"}
\par 
\item Partner 1 believes that with probably $0.25$ Partner 2 plays Listen, and with probability $0.75$ plays Argue. 
\item Partner 1's expected utility from these beliefs are:
\[EU_1(Listen)=0.25 \times 0+0.75 \times (-1)=-0.75.
\]
\[EU_1(Argue)=0.25\times 1 +0.75 \times (-2)=-1.25.
\]

\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}{Mixed Strategy}
    \begin{table}[]
\centering

\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Partner 2}                                    \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Partner 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Argue} \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-1, 1}   \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Argue}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,-1}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-2,-2}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Partner 1 is thinking:
\par 
 \textit{"If my partner listens to me, I would argue my point. However, from the past I know that $25\%$ of the time my partner listens to me, and $75\%$ of the time my partner argues. What is the best for me, to argue or to listen?"}
\par 
 
\item Partner 1's expected utility from Listening is higher than from Arguing, since $EU(Listen)=-0.75 > -1.25=EU(Argue).$
\item Therefore, in the best response of Partner 1 is to listen. 

\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Mixed Strategies}
\begin{itemize}
    \item We enlarge the set of strategies for the players.
    \item Instead of choosing a single element from $S_i$ (a pure strategy), we
allow players to choose a probability distribution over $S_i$.

\end{itemize}
    \begin{block}{Definition}
    Let $S_i=\{s_{i1}, s_{i2},..., s_{im}\}$ be player $i$'s finite set of pure strategies. Define $\Delta S_i$ as set of all probability distributions over $S_i$. A mixed strategy for player $i$ is a probability distribution over pure strategies, such that:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item $\sigma_i(s_i)\geq 0$, for all $s_i \in S_i$,
        \item $\sigma_1+\sigma_2+...+\sigma_m=1$.
    \end{enumerate}
    \end{block}
    \end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Mixed Strategies}
  \begin{table}[]
\centering

\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Partner 2}                                    \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Partner 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Argue} \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-1, 1}   \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Argue}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,-1}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-2,-2}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{itemize}
\item $S_1=\{  Listen, Argue \}$, $\Delta S_1= \{ (\sigma_1, \sigma_2)\}$ such that $\sigma_1+\sigma_2=1$, and $\sigma_1 \in [0,1]$, $\sigma_2 \in [0,1]$.
\item \textbf{Examples of mixed strategy:} $(\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{2})$,  $(\frac{1}{3}, \frac{2}{3})$, $(0.9, 0.1)$. 

\item \textbf{ Not so good examples: } $(0.7, 0.8)$, $(-0.2, -0.8)$, $(25, 75)$, $(50, 50)$. 
\item In the first case you can see that all the probabilities are between $[0,1]$, and they sum up to 1. 
\item In the second example, however, at least one of those conditions is violated. 
\end{itemize}
 \end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Mixed Strategies}
\begin{itemize}
    \item We can find best response correspondence not only for pure strategies, but also for the mixed strategies. 
\end{itemize}
  \begin{table}[]
\centering

\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Partner 2}                                    \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Partner 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Argue} \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-1, 1}   \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Argue}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,-1}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-2,-2}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{itemize}
    \item Suppose Partner 1 is mixing between  Listen and Argue $(0.8, 0.2)$. 
    \item In order to understand the best response of Partner 2, we need to calculate the expected payoff from Listening and Arguing.
    \[EU_2(Listen)=0.8 \times 0+0.2 \times (-1)=-0.2.
\]
\[EU_2(Argue)=0.8\times 1 +0.2 \times (-2)=0.4.
\]
    \item Since $EU_2(Argue) > EU_2(Listen)$, then it is better for Partner 2 to Argue. 
\end{itemize}
 \end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example 5: Homework}

  \begin{table}[]
\centering

\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Partner 2}                                    \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Partner 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Argue} \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Listen} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-1, 1}   \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{Argue}       & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,-1}         & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{-2,-2}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Suppose Partner 2 is mixing with probabilities $(0.3, 0.7)$. What are the expected utilities of Partner 1 from Listening and Arguing? What is the best response of Partner 1? 
  \item Repeat the exercise for the following probabilities: 
  $(0.1, 0.9)$, $(0.2, 0.8)$, $(0.9, 0.1)$, $(0.7, 0.3)$, $(0.5,0.5)$. 
  \item Given the probabilities of Partner 2, when is it best for Partner 1 to Argue?
  \item Now suppose Partner 1 is mixing with probabilities $(0.3, 0.7)$. What are the expected utilities of Partner 2 from Listening and Arguing? What is the best response of Partner 2? Is it different from the best response of the Partner 1?
\end{itemize}


\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Summary}
\begin{itemize}
    \item We introduced and discussed the best response correspondence. 
    \item To calculate best response, we need to understand what is the best strategy for each player. By best, we mean the one that gives highest payoff. 
    \item Then, we introduced mixed strategy, and we studied best response correspondence for mixed strategies. 
    \item \textbf{ Assignment 1 is due next Monday, 11:59 pm.}
\end{itemize}
    
\end{frame}



